'''Katsuragi Hitokotonushi Shrine''' (かつらぎひとことぬしじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Gose City|Q847334|qid=Q847334|1=Gose, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|qid=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=Myōjin Taisha|Q9610964|qid=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), and under the {{ill|lt=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=former shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was designated a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}. It is commonly known as “Ichigon-san” or “Ichikon-ji-san.” The shrine is enshrined facing east on the eastern foothills of {{ill|lt=Mount Yamato Katsuragi|Q11433560|qid=Q11433560|lt=Mount Katsuragi|1=Mount Yamato Katsuragi}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The shrine enshrines the following two deities<ref name="由緒書">Shrine history pamphlet.</ref>.
* {{ill|lt=Hitokotonushi|Q10864079|qid=Q10864079|lt=Katsuragi no Hitokotonushi Ōkami|1=Hitokotonushi}} (かつらぎのひとことぬしのおおかみ) – principal deity.
* {{ill|lt=Emperor Yūryaku|Q357235|qid=Q357235|lt=Wakatakeru no Mikoto|1=Emperor Yūryaku}} (わかたけるのみこと) – the 21st Emperor Yūryaku.

The Meiji-era *Shrine Register* lists the two deities as Kotoshironushi no Mikoto and Wakatakeru no Mikoto, while the *Yamato Shiryō* states that Hitokotonushi is the main deity with Emperor Yūryaku enshrined jointly{{Sfn|葛木坐一言主神社（神々）|1985年}}{{Sfn|奈良県史 5|1989年|pp=449-450}}. In the *{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}* {{ill|lt=Register of Deities|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, the shrine has one seat, and appears as “Katsuki-ni-masu Hitokotonushi Shrine,” indicating that it originally enshrined only {{ill|lt=Hitokotonushi|Q10864079|qid=Q10864079|lt=Hitokotonushi|1=Hitokotonushi}}{{Sfn|葛木坐一言主神社（神々）|1985年}}. This deity is written as “Hitokotonushi” in the *{{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|qid=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}*, “Hito-kotonushi” in the *{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|qid=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}*, and “Hito-go-nushi” in the *{{ill|lt=Nihon Ryōiki|Q1606838|qid=Q1606838|lt=Nihon Ryōiki|1=Nihon Ryōiki}}*<ref group="原" name="日本霊異記"/>. He is regarded as a god of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=oracles|1=UNKNOWN}}, who utters both good and ill fortune in a single word, and is still worshiped today as a deity who grants wishes with a single utterance{{Sfn|一言主神社（平凡社）|1981年}}. Although no genealogy is recorded in the *Kojiki* or *Nihon Shoki*, the *{{ill|lt=Sendai Kuji Hongi|Q2716751|qid=Q2716751|1=Kujiki}}*<ref group="原">“Sendai Kuji Hongi,” *Chigi Honki*.</ref> identifies Hitokotonushi as a child of {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}{{Sfn|一言主神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

[[File:Tennō Yūryaku.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{Center|{{ill|lt=Emperor Yūryaku|Q357235|qid=Q357235|1=Emperor Yūryaku}} and the great boar of {{ill|lt=Mount Yamato Katsuragi|Q11433560|qid=Q11433560|lt=Mount Katsuragi|1=Mount Yamato Katsuragi}}}}]]
Regarding Hitokotonushi, a well-known encounter tale with {{ill|lt=Emperor Yūryaku|Q357235|qid=Q357235|1=Emperor Yūryaku}} appears in both the *Nihon Shoki*<ref group="原">*Nihon Shoki*, Emperor Yūryaku, 4th year, 2nd month.</ref> and the *Kojiki*<ref group="原">*Kojiki*, section on Emperor Yūryaku.</ref>. According to both accounts, while Emperor Yūryaku was hunting in the mountains of Katsuragi, Hitokotonushi (also written as Hito-kotonushi), who appeared in the same form as the emperor, emerged and competed with him in the hunt{{Sfn|一言主神社（平凡社）|1981年}}. In the *Kojiki*, however, the emperor offers a great sword, bow and arrows, and many garments to the deity and worships him, portraying Hitokotonushi as superior, whereas in the *Nihon Shoki* the emperor makes no such offerings and the two are depicted as nearly equal in status{{Sfn|葛木坐一言主神社（神々）|1985年}}. Since the *Kojiki* is considered more archaic, its account is thought to reflect the political circumstances when the {{ill|lt=Katsuragi clan|Q11620908|qid=Q11620908|1=Katsuragi clan}}—regarded as the clan responsible for the worship of Hitokotonushi—held strong power as imperial in-laws, whereas the *Nihon Shoki* reflects a later period when the Katsuragi clan declined and the status of Hitokotonushi diminished{{Sfn|葛木坐一言主神社（神々）|1985年}}<ref>*Shinpen Nihon Koten Bungaku Zenshū 3: Nihon Shoki (2)*, Shogakukan, 2004 (JapanKnowledge edition), pp. 158–160.</ref>.

In later periods, in Heian-era works such as the *{{ill|lt=Nihon Ryōiki|Q1606838|qid=Q1606838|lt=Nihon Ryōiki|1=Nihon Ryōiki}}*<ref group="原" name="日本霊異記">*Nihon Ryōiki*, volume 28.</ref> and the *{{ill|lt=Konjaku Monogatari-shū|Q1507085|qid=Q1507085|1=Konjaku Monogatarishū}}*<ref group="原">*Konjaku Monogatari-shū*, volume 11, story 3.</ref>, Hitokotonushi is described as being conscripted by {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=En no Gyōja|1=UNKNOWN}} (En no Ubasoku / En no Ozunu) to build a bridge between {{ill|lt=Mount Kinpu|Q10563986|qid=Q10563986|1=Mount Kinpusen}} and Mount Katsuragi, and even bound by a curse after incurring En no Gyōja’s anger—indicating a further decline in divine authority{{Sfn|葛木坐一言主神社（神々）|1985年}}. It is also said that during this forced labor, Hitokotonushi hid the ugliness of his face and worked only at night, not by day; inspired by this tale, {{ill|lt=Matsuo Bashō|Q5676|qid=Q5676|1=Matsuo Bashō}} composed a poem in *Oi no Kobumi* (see “{{ill|lt=#Appearances in works|UNKNOWN|lt=Appearances in works}}”){{Sfn|葛木坐一言主神社（神々）|1985年}}.

[[File:Tosa-jinja torii.JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|{{ill|lt=Tosa Shrine|Q704890|qid=Q704890|1=Tosa Shrine}} ({{ill|lt=Kōchi Prefecture|Q134093|qid=Q134093|1=Kōchi Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Kōchi City|Q200251|qid=Q200251|1=Kōchi, Kōchi}})}}{{small|Currently enshrines {{ill|lt=Hitokotonushi|Q10864079|qid=Q10864079|lt=Hitokotonushi|1=Hitokotonushi}} and {{ill|lt=Ajisukitakahikone|UNKNOWN|lt=Ajisukitakahikone no Kami}}.}}]]
According to the *{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|qid=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}}*, entry for the 8th year of {{ill|lt=Tenpyō-hōji|Q1346307|qid=Q1346307|1=Tenpyō-hōji}} ({{ill|lt=764|Q31163|qid=Q31163|1=764}})<ref group="原">*Shoku Nihongi*, Tenpyō-hōji 8 (764), 11th month, day 7.</ref>, a deity called “Takakamo no Kami,” who had competed in hunting with Emperor Yūryaku, had been exiled to {{ill|lt=Tosa Province|Q857330|qid=Q857330|1=Tosa Province}}, but in that year was re-enshrined in his original place{{Sfn|一言主神社（平凡社）|1981年}}. However, one passage cited in the *{{ill|lt=Shaku Nihongi|Q2710483|qid=Q2710483|1=Shaku Nihongi}}* from the *Rekiryoku* states that in Tenpyō-hōji 8, Hitokotonushi was brought back from Tosa and enshrined in Katsuragi{{Sfn|一言主神社（平凡社）|1981年}}. Another excerpt from the *Tosa Province Fudoki* cited in the *Shaku Nihongi* notes that the deity of Takakamo Taisha in Tosa (present-day {{ill|lt=Tosa Shrine|Q704890|qid=Q704890|1=Tosa Shrine}}) is Hitokotonushi no Mikoto, though another tradition identifies him as {{ill|lt=Ajisukitakahikone|Q506610|qid=Q506610|lt=Ajisukitakahikone no Mikoto|1=Ajisukitakahikone}}. Thus, the sources show confusion between Hitokotonushi and Takakamo no Kami (Ajisukitakahikone no Mikoto, enshrined at {{ill|lt=Takakamo Shrine|Q11673295|qid=Q11673295|1=Takakamo Shrine}}){{Sfn|平林章仁|2013年|pp=235-253}}. Additionally, due to similarities in name and their nature as oracle deities, some theories identify Hitokotonushi with {{ill|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi|Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi no Mikoto|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}}{{Sfn|一言主神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

=== History ===
The date of foundation is unknown. Shrine tradition holds that the current site is where Hitokotonushi manifested<ref name="由緒書"/>.

In the {{ill|lt=Six National Histories|Q1151168|qid=Q1151168|lt=official histories|1=Rikkokushi}}, it is recorded that in the 3rd year of {{ill|lt=Kashō|Q1373157|qid=Q1373157|1=Kashō}} ({{ill|lt=850|Q30364|qid=Q30364|1=850}})<ref group="原" name="嘉祥3年"/>, the divine rank of “Katsuki Hitokotonushi no Kami” was raised to Senior Third Rank, and that in the 3rd year of {{ill|lt=Ten’an (Japanese era)|Q1075611|qid=Q1075611|lt=Ten’an|1=Ten'an}} ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|qid=Q23897|1=859}}) in the first month<ref group="原" name="貞観元年正月"/>, it was promoted to Junior Second Rank, Second Class of Merit{{Sfn|葛城坐一言主神社（式内社）|1982年}}. In September of the same year, the first year of {{ill|lt=Jōgan (Japanese era)|Q1075635|qid=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} (859)<ref group="原">*Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku*, Jōgan 1 (859), 9th month, 8th day (see {{Harvnb|神道・神社史料集成}}).</ref>, envoys were dispatched to present offerings to Hitokotonushi and other deities in prayer for rain and wind{{Sfn|葛城坐一言主神社（式内社）|1982年}}. In the 5th year of {{ill|lt=Shōryaku|Q1324858|qid=Q1324858|1=Shōryaku}} ({{ill|lt=994|Q24114|qid=Q24114|1=994}}), fourth month<ref group="原">*Honchō Seiki*, Shōryaku 5 (994), 4th month.</ref>, offerings were again presented, with members of the {{ill|lt=Nakatomi clan|Q1198447|qid=Q1198447|1=Nakatomi clan}} serving as envoys, in response to epidemics and fires{{Sfn|一言主神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

In the *{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}* {{ill|lt=Register of Deities|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, compiled in the 5th year of {{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}), the shrine is listed in Yamato Province, {{ill|lt=Katsukami District|Q11620858|qid=Q11620858|1=Katsujō district}}, as “Katsuki-ni-masu Hitokotonushi Shrine, Myōjin Taisha, Monthly and New Harvest Offerings,” indicating its status as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Myōjin Taisha|1=UNKNOWN}} and that it received offerings from the court at the {{ill|lt=Monthly Rite|Q11516161|qid=Q11516161|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri}} and {{ill|lt=New Harvest Festival|Q11501518|qid=Q11501518|1=Niiname-no-Matsuri}}{{Sfn|葛城坐一言主神社（式内社）|1982年}}.

Subsequent history is unclear. In the past, there was a temple called Ichigon-ji to the southeast of the shrine as a {{ill|lt=jingū-ji|Q1074971|qid=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}}, but it has since been abandoned{{Sfn|一言主神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|qid=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, in {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6), the shrine was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} under the {{ill|lt=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, and in March {{ill|lt=1883|Q7816|qid=Q7816|1=1883}} (Meiji 16) it was promoted to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}{{Sfn|明治神社誌料|1912年}}.

=== Divine ranks ===
* {{ill|lt=Kashō|Q1373157|qid=Q1373157|1=Kashō}} 3 ({{ill|lt=850|Q30364|qid=Q30364|1=850}}), October 7: Senior Third Rank (*{{ill|lt=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|Q1052905|qid=Q1052905|1=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku}}*)<ref group="原" name="嘉祥3年">*Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku*, Kashō 3 (850), 10th month, day 7 (see {{Harvnb|神道・神社史料集成}}).</ref> – recorded as “Katsuki Hitokotonushi no Kami.”
* {{ill|lt=Ten’an (Japanese era)|Q1075611|qid=Q1075611|lt=Ten’an|1=Ten'an}} 3 ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|qid=Q23897|1=859}}), January 27: Promoted from Senior Third Rank, Second Class of Merit to Junior Second Rank, Second Class of Merit (*{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}*)<ref group="原" name="貞観元年正月">*Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku*, Jōgan 1 (859), 1st month, 27th day (see {{Harvnb|神道・神社史料集成}}).</ref> – recorded as “Katsuki Hitokotonushi no Kami.”

=== Shrine grounds ===
[[File:Katusragi-hitokotonushi-jinja icho.jpg|thumb|180px|{{center|Lactiferous ginkgo}}]]
* Main hall – Rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1876|Q7766|qid=Q7766|1=1876}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 9). One-bay {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|qid=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}} style, with a copper-sheet roof{{Sfn|葛城坐一言主神社（式内社）|1982年}}.
* Worship hall – In front of the hall stands an ancient {{ill|lt=ginkgo|Q43284|qid=Q43284|1=Ginkgo biloba}} tree (the lactiferous ginkgo), said to be 1,200 years old and regarded as a sacred tree.
* Offering hall
* Shrine office
* Spider Mound – A mound based on legends of {{ill|lt=Emperor Jimmu|Q200188|qid=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}}’s subjugation of the {{ill|lt=earth spiders|Q2063089|qid=Q2063089|1=Tsuchigumo}}{{Sfn|葛木坐一言主神社（神々）|1985年}}.
* Great Rite Memorial Hall
* Statue of {{ill|lt=Emperor Yūryaku|Q357235|qid=Q357235|1=Emperor Yūryaku}}
* Hōrai Stone
* Turtle Stone

=== Auxiliary and branch shrines ===
* Jingū Kōgō Shrine – Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|qid=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}}
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Tenman Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} – Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|qid=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hachiman Shrine|1=Hachiman shrine|qid=Q11390939}} – Enshrined deities: {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|qid=Q317997|lt=Hondawake no Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin}}, {{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|qid=Q232803|lt=Okinaga Tarashihime no Mikoto|1=Empress Jingū}}
* Ichikishima Shrine – Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Ichikishimahime|Q11059454|qid=Q11059454|lt=Ichikishimahime no Mikoto|1=Ichikishima-hime}}
* Hitokoto {{ill|lt=Inari Shrine|Q514480|qid=Q514480|1=Inari shrine}} – Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Ukemochi|Q2280323|qid=Q2280323|1=Ukemochi}}
* Haraedo Shrine – Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Seoritsuhime|Q13579836|qid=Q13579836|1=Seoritsu-hime}} no Mikoto
* {{ill|lt=Sumiyoshi Shrine|Q11381857|qid=Q11381857|1=Sumiyoshi Shrine}} – Enshrined deities: {{ill|lt=Sumiyoshi Sanjin|Q1114013|qid=Q1114013|lt=Sokotsutsuo no Mikoto, Nakatsutsuo no Mikoto, Uwatsutsuo no Mikoto|1=Sumiyoshi sanjin}}, Okinaga Tarashihime no Mikoto
* Okumiya – About 50 meters west of the main hall, a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=iwakura|1=UNKNOWN}} is enshrined as the inner shrine.
